{"id":"1905.05548","submitter":"Bikash Bhattacharjya <","authors":"Deepak Sehrawat, Bikash Bhattacharjya","title":"Maximum Frustration in Signed Generalized Petersen Graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Indian journal of discrete mathematics, vol 5, no. 2 (2019) ,\n  77-93","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A \\textit{signed graph} is a simple graph whose edges are labelled with\npositive or negative signs. A cycle is \\textit{positive} if the product of its\nedge signs is positive. A signed graph is \\textit{balanced} if every cycle in\nthe graph is positive. The \\textit{frustration index} of a signed graph is the\nminimum number of edges whose deletion makes the graph balanced. The\n\\textit{maximum frustration} of a graph is the maximum frustration index over\nall sign labellings. In this paper, first, we prove that the maximum\nfrustration of generalized Petersen graphs $P_{n,k}$ is bounded above by\n$\\left\\lfloor \\frac{n}{2} \\right\\rfloor + 1$ for $\\gcd(n,k)=1$, and this bound\nis achieved for $k=1,2,3$. Second, we prove that the maximum frustration of\n$P_{n,k}$ is bounded above by $d\\left\\lfloor \\frac{n}{2d} \\right\\rfloor + d +\n1$, where $\\gcd(n,k)=d\\geq2$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 14 May 2019 12:27:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-10-12"}
